04320nam a22005295i 9780773598522DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735985227 a10.1515/97807735985222doi  a(DE-B1597)658018  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR428.P93bB43 2016eb 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a820.9/3532231 aBeecher, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAdapted Brains and Imaginary Worlds :bCognitive Science and the Literature of the Renaissance /cDonald Beecher. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOn the Obsessions of Selfhood -- tThe Biogenesis of Ethics and the Challenge of Shakespeare’s Measure for Measure -- tOn the Emotional Intentionality of Criminal Protagonists -- tOn the Systemic Properties of Recollection -- tCrying and the Ambiguity of Shakespeare’s -- tToward a Cognitive Theory of Proverbs -- tRomance and the Universality of Human Nature -- tSuspense .... -- tLaughter’s Shortfall -- tCognition, Conversion, and the Patterns of Religious Experience -- tFolk Psychology and Theory of Mind John Marston’s The Fawn -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Adapted Brains and Imaginary Worlds, Donald Beecher explores the characteristics and idiosyncrasies of the brain as they affect the study of fiction. He builds upon insights from the cognitive sciences to explain how we actualize imaginary persons, read the clues to their intentional states, assess their representations of selfhood, and empathize with their felt experiences in imaginary environments. He considers how our own faculty of memory, in all its selective particularity and planned oblivion, becomes an increasingly significant dimension of the critical act, and how our own emotions become aggressive readers of literary experience, culminating in states which define the genres of literature. Beecher illustrates his points with examples from major works of the Renaissance period, including Dr Faustus, The Faerie Queene, Measure for Measure, The Yorkshire Tragedy, Menaphon, The Dialogue of Solomon and Marcolphus, and The Moral Philosophy of Doni. In this volume, studies in the science of mind come into their own in explaining the architectures of the brain that shape such emergent properties as empathy, suspense, curiosity, the formation of communities, gossip, rationalization, confabulation, and so much more that pertains to the behaviour of characters, the orientation of readers, and the construction of meaning. Discussing a breadth of topics – from the mysteries of the criminal mind to the psychology of tears – Adapted Brains and Imaginary Worlds is the most comprehensive work available on the study of fictional worlds and their relation to the constitution of the human brain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCognition in literature. 0aCognitive science. 0aEmotions in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aMemory in literature. 0aPsychology in literature. 0aSelf in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359852240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773598522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773598522/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles